49 /* THE INDEX PAGE
50 ==============
51
52 The index page consists of a page header which contains the page's
53 id and other information. On top of it are the index records
54 in a heap linked into a one way linear list according to alphabetic order.
55
56 Just below page end is an array of pointers which we call page directory,
57 to about every sixth record in the list. The pointers are placed in
58 the directory in the alphabetical order of the records pointed to,
59 enabling us to make binary search using the array. Each slot n:o I
60 in the directory points to a record, where a 4-bit field contains a count
61 of those records which are in the linear list between pointer I and
62 the pointer I - 1 in the directory, including the record
63 pointed to by pointer I and not including the record pointed to by I - 1.
64 We say that the record pointed to by slot I, or that slot I, owns
65 these records. The count is always kept in the range 4 to 8, with
66 the exception that it is 1 for the first slot, and 1--8 for the second slot.
67
68 An essentially binary search can be performed in the list of index
69 records, like we could do if we had pointer to every record in the
70 page directory. The data structure is, however, more efficient when
71 we are doing inserts, because most inserts are just pushed on a heap.
72 Only every 8th insert requires block move in the directory pointer
73 table, which itself is quite small. A record is deleted from the page
74 by just taking it off the linear list and updating the number of owned
75 records-field of the record which owns it, and updating the page directory,
76 if necessary. A special case is the one when the record owns itself.
77 Because the overhead of inserts is so small, we may also increase the
78 page size from the projected default of 8 kB to 64 kB without too
79 much loss of efficiency in inserts. Bigger page becomes actual
80 when the disk transfer rate compared to seek and latency time rises.
81 On the present system, the page size is set so that the page transfer
82 time (3 ms) is 20 % of the disk random access time (15 ms).
83
84 When the page is split, merged, or becomes full but contains deleted
85 records, we have to reorganize the page.
86
87 Assuming a page size of 8 kB, a typical index page of a secondary
88 index contains 300 index entries, and the size of the page directory
89 is 50 x 4 bytes = 200 bytes. */
90
